{{Infobox company | name = Corder Drum Company | logo = | type = | industry = [[Percussion instrument]]s | fate = Acquired by Sammy Darwin | predecessor = <!-- or: | predecessors = --> | successor = <!-- or: | successors = --> | founded = 1979 | founder = Jim Corder | defunct = 1990 | hq_location_city = [[Huntsville, Alabama]] | hq_location_country = | area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = --> | key_people = | products = | owner = <!-- or: | owners = --> | num_employees = | num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) --> | parent = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
'''Corder Drum Company''' was a [[percussion instrument]] manufacturing company based in [[Huntsville, Alabama]]. The company was created in 1979 by Jim Corder, following his purchase of the dies, moulds and tooling apparatus of the [[Fibes Drums|Fibes Drum]] Company from its then-owner, the [[C. F. Martin & Company|C.F. Martin Organization]].<ref>Nicholls, Geoff; Slingsby, Miki; and Bacon, Tony (1997). ''The Drum Book: A History of the Rock Drum Kit'', Backbeat Books. {{ISBN|0-87930-476-6}}</ref> Corder Drum manufactured a line of wood shell drums using Fibes-designed lugs, strainers and hoops until 1990, when Corder sold his company to Sammy Darwin, a [[radio]] programmer who renamed the operation Darwin Drums.<ref name=GAD>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glC-iCcY6CUC&pg=PA9&lpg=PA9&dq=%22jim+corder%22+%22huntsville,+alabama%22&source=web&ots=yr9LcjvDL3&sig=wdxwUtPxVi95T5woqrTfTv-M6u4&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=1&ct=result |title=The Great American Drums and the Companies that Made Them, 1920–1969 |first=Harry |last=Cangany|author2=Van Horn, Rick|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation |year=1996|isbn=0-7935-6356-9}}</ref> Four years later, Darwin sold the company to Tommy Robertson, who brought back the Fibes Drum Company name for the product line.<ref name=GAD />
